,Not Recommended,305800,18209325,"Posted: 26 September, 2015",all,Theyrvalls,"What is POP: Methodology Experiment One ?Genre: adventure, told in different, non-canonical scenesSetting: different 20th century themed scenes, both famous and common, to be travelled by the playerDifficulty: 0/10 --> you progress, no matter what. 9/10 if going for achievementsLength: about an hour for a single playthroughMode: singleplayer campaign, replayable ""vignettes"" (=scenes)The positive aspects:- different scenes from 20th century's history, such as manned spaceflight, mignight air raid, boarding a helicopter in a war territory- strange scenes mix with bad resolution videos and lets you guess what the story or moral of the game could be (This could also be on the negative side, though)The negative aspects:- Horrible controls. In some scenes, you don't know if pressing keys does affect the game at all- The options menu is no use at all. rebinding keys does not work- Loading times. For just a small scene, it can take a modern computer up to half a minute to load- General slowness. Press a button for two seconds to continue here, press it for six seconds to continue there. Seriously: WTF?!- No storytelling, no moral, no underlined questions, no nothing.- Considering these aspects, getting all achievements will become a tough challenge, to say the leastResult (and summary for those who have no time reading):POP's an art game designed by some art-related guy for art students primarily. At least that's what it felt like for me. Actually, being an enthusiastic player of games with a little weird spin, playing it didn't enrich me at all. Plus, short length, screwed controls and loading times impair the playing experience negatively.Thus I do not recommend buying this game at all."
